        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley | Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Oct 23<hi rend="superscript">rd</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I asked D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Gray to tell Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Ticknor &amp; Field that you would let them have 250 copies of New Edit. of Origin at <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></formula> price; but a letter from Gray has crossed mine on the road.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> He sends the enclosed note from Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Ticknor, which I do not understand for I do not see what “Da &amp; Co” means.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Anyhow Gray says that they are afraid of the Appletons &amp; will not publish an edit. of my new book. You see they recommend, as does Gray that you sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> send copies for the American Market.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> But there is no hurry about this.</p>
<p>With respect to the Origin I do not suppose that Gray will communicate again with Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Ticknor &amp; Field &amp; it is not fair to ask him to take any more trouble. So you must do what you think best about sending copies of the Origin to some House in America.</p>
<p>Gray is going to review the new edit. &amp; evidently thinks there would be some sale for it.<ref target="#foot.f5"/> It has just occurred to me that if Gray does communicate with Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Ticknor &amp; they accept the 250 copies it would be an awkward predicament if they were sent elsewhere. You must decide what had better be done.</p>
<p>My dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>Please let me hear what you decide.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.4 see] <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand over</hi> ‘say’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.4 what] <hi rend="italic">interl in CD’s hand</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">4.1 Ch. Darwin … decide.—- 5.1] <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5237.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Asa Gray, 10 October 1866</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5246.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 18 October [1866]</ref>. Gray had approached the Boston firm of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4752.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ticknor &amp; Fields</ref> about publishing the fourth edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> as well as <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref>, but had recently informed CD that they had declined both offers (see letters from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1957.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Asa Gray</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5160.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">18 July 1866</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5198.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">27 August 1866</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5237.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">10 October 1866</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The enclosure has not been found. The reference is to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_135.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Appleton &amp; Co</ref>., which CD usually referred to as ‘Appletons’. They were reluctant to bring out a new edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> because of typesetting difficulties (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5210.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Asa Gray, 10 September [1866]</ref> and n. 7).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5237.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Asa Gray, 10 October 1866</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">No review by Gray of the fourth edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> has been found.</note>
        </div>        
            
